07770nam a22010335i 9780231548007DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20202021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020018243  a97802315480077 a10.7312/harg188762doi  a(DE-B1597)566354  a(OCoLC)1225551612  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aH61b.R4647 2020 7aSOC0190002bisacsh04a300.72223  aMR 20002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123487:1 aHargittai, Eszter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aResearch Exposed :bHow Empirical Social Science Gets Done in the Digital Age /cEszter Hargittai. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One When Social Media Data Disappear -- tChapter Two The Needle in the Haystack: Finding Social Bots on Twitter -- tChapter Three Meeting Youth Where They Are: Challenges and Lessons Learned from Social Media Recruitment for Sexual and Gender Minority Youth -- tChapter Four Qualitative Sampling and Internet Research -- tChapter Five Behind the Red Lights: Methods for Investigating the Digital Security and Privacy Experiences of Sex Workers -- tChapter Six Using Unexpected Data to Study Up: Washington Political Journalism (and the Case of the Missing Press Pass) -- tChapter Seven Social Media and Ethnographic Relationships -- tChapter Eight Ethnographic Research with People Experiencing Homelessness in the Digital Age -- tChapter Nine Going Rural: Personal Notes from a Mixed-Methods Project on Digital Media in Remote Communities -- tChapter Ten Stitching Data: A Multimodal Approach to Learning About Independent Artists’ Social Media Use -- tChapter Eleven A Measurement Burst Study of Media Use and Well-Being Among Older Adults: Logistically Challenging at Best -- tChapter Twelve Community-Based Intervention Research Strategies: Digital Inclusion for Marginalized Populations -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe era of digital communication provides endless opportunities for the collection and analysis of social data in novel ways. It also presents new and unanticipated challenges, as researchers are often inventing elements of their methodologies on the fly or studying a phenomenon or media platform for the first time.Research Exposed offers in-depth, behind-the-scenes accounts of doing empirical social science in this new paradigm. Through firsthand descriptions of innovative research projects, it shares lessons learned from over a dozen scholars’ cutting-edge work. These candid accounts describe what can go wrong when pioneering new genres of research and how such difficulties can be overcome, giving both big-picture reflection and actionable advice. The chapters discuss a variety of methods, ranging from the completely novel to the use of more traditional approaches in the digital context, and cover research questions relevant to a range of disciplines, including sociology, political science, communication, information studies, and anthropology.By focusing attention on the concrete details seldom discussed in final project write-ups or traditional research guides, Research Exposed helps equip junior and senior scholars alike with essential information that is all too often left with no outlet for sharing. It offers important insights into how empirical social science research can be both innovative and rigorous when dealing with the opportunities and challenges presented by digital media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDigital mediaxResearch. 0aInternet research. 0aSocial mediaxResearch. 0aSocial sciencesxMethodology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENC